http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: 21st Century Dance Content Standards and Objectives for West Virginia Schools

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Dance is a means of communication and self-expression different from the written or spoken word, or from visual and auditory symbol systems. Dance is a performing art ideally taught sequentially with each level reinforcing and building upon skills taught at previous levels. Dance education is a study of "the art of dance" as well as the techniques involved in the various styles. As students learn and share dances from their own communities and other cultures, they gain skills and knowledge that will prepare them to become responsive participants in an increasingly global society, with a better understanding of dance from a recreational or vocational viewpoint. Each level of dance provides opportunities to correlate dance activities with other subjects thereby enriching learning.
Dance I
Communication
Students will use dance as a way to create and communicate meaning.
observe and explain how personal experience can influence the individual interpretation of a movement.
recognize and communicate abstract ideas through movement.
identify and conclude the distinguishing moment when movement becomes dance (when movement takes on purpose and intent it becomes dance).
improvise a movement phrase that communicates a relevant social theme.
Movement, Elements and Skills
Students will develop and practice movement elements in performing dance.
identify and practice locomotor and nonlocomotor/axial movements with an awareness of alignment.
identify and practice steps and patterns from several different dance styles/traditions.
understand rhythm and timing as it relates to movement.
recognize and demonstrate the various dance concepts.
practice extended movement sequences.
Healthful Living
Students will relate dance to physical health.
understand and apply health related concepts to dance.
examine personal physical health and identify strengths and weaknesses to formulate goals.
identify lifestyle choices and their affect on the dancer.
Cultures and Historical Periods
Students will examine and demonstrate dance from various cultures and historical periods.
perform and report on the history of culturally diverse dances.
identify the four dance forms and give examples of each
research and answer questions about dance and dancers prior to the twentieth century.
discuss dance and dancers as perceived in contemporary media when compared to other time periods and cultures.
Critical and Creative Thinking Skills
Students will employ critical and creative thinking skills in dance.
create a series of dance phrases and revise them over time.
establish a set of aesthetic criteria and apply it in evaluating student work.
answer aesthetic questions in a group setting.
Choreography
Students will understand and apply choreographic principles, processes and structures.
identify, define and practice elements of choreography.
identify, define and practice choreographic forms through the creation of a movement phrase.
examine improvisation as a method for generating movement for choreography.
Connections with Other Disciplines
Students will connect dance to other disciplines.
create a group interdisciplinary project based on a theme identified by the group.
discuss how technology can be used to reinforce, enhance or alter the dance idea.
identify and discuss commonalities and differences between dance and other disciplines with regard to fundamental concepts such as materials, elements and ways of communicating meaning.
Dance II
Communication
Students will use dance as a way to create and communicate meaning.
articulate understanding of how personal experience influences the interpretation of a dance
use improvisation to prepare a movement phrase that communicates abstract ideas.
collaborate to create a dance that communicates a relevant social theme.
Movement, Elements and Skills
Students will develop and practice movement elements in performing dance.
demonstrate correct alignment.
identify and demonstrate longer and more complex steps and patterns from several dance styles/traditions.
demonstrate rhythm and timing during movement.
modify the dance concepts to reconstruct a dance phrase.
articulate the importance of projection while performing dance skills.
demonstrate the ability to remember extended movement sequences.
Healthful Living
Students will relate dance to physical health.
assess personal physical health goals in order to revise and refine.
describe how specific lifestyle choices affect the dancer.
research historical and cultural images of the body as it relates to dance.
Cultures and Historical Periods
Students will examine and demonstrate dance from various cultures and historical periods
perform and differentiate between two or more culturally diverse dances.
examine and discuss the traditions and techniques of recreational and aerobic forms of dance.
answer questions about dance and dancers within the twentieth century.
research and analyze how dance and dancers are perceived in contemporary media when compared to other time periods and cultures.
Critical and Creative Thinking Skills
Students will employ critical and creative thinking skills in dance
create a dance and revise it over time, explaining the revisions and their impact on the final product.
apply aesthetic criteria to evaluate the student's own work and the work of others in a positive and constructive manner.
formulate and answer aesthetic questions based on a performance
Choreography
Students will understand and apply choreographic principles, processes and structures.
create and perform a dance phrase containing three to five elements of choreography.
create and perform a dance phrase using at least two choreographic forms.
employ improvisation to generate movement for choreography.
Connections with Other Disciplines
Students will connect dance to other disciplines.
create an interdisciplinary project based on a theme identified by the student, including dance and two other disciplines.
demonstrate how technology can be used to reinforce, enhance or alter the dance idea in an interdisciplinary project.
Dance III
Communication
Students will use dance as a way to create and communicate meaning.
research and incorporate other viewpoints when creating dance to convey meaning.
create and perform (in class) an individual dance conveying a personal experience, belief or theme.
Movement, Elements and Skills
Students will develop and practice movement elements in performing dance.
understand clarity and stylistic nuance.
perform, consistently, rhythm and timing during a movement phrase or dance.
model projection while performing.
assess technique/skills through self-evaluation.
Healthful Living
Students will relate dance to physical health.
devise a plan to incorporate their personal health goals throughout life.
research and discuss the challenges facing performers in maintaining healthy lifestyles.
analyze historical and cultural images of the body in dance and compare these to the images of the body in contemporary media.
Cultures and Historical Periods
Students will examine and demonstrate dance from various cultures and historical periods.
compare and contrast the role and significance of dance in two different historical/cultural/political contexts.
examine and discuss the traditions and techniques of creative and concert forms of dance
perform a dance that displays the traditions and techniques of a specific culture or historical period.
Critical and Creative Thinking Skills
Students will employ critical and creative thinking skills in dance
discuss and research how skills developed in dance are applicable to a variety of careers (e.g., sports, modeling, secretary, therapist).
research and analyze the styles of several choreographers or dance companies.
research and discuss issues of ethnicity, gender, social/economic class, age and/or physical condition in relation to dance.
Choreography
Students will understand and apply choreographic principles, processes and structures.
apply choreographic principles in creating a small group dance with coherence and aesthetic unity.
research and analyze the creative process of choreographers (e.g., video biographies, interviews).
Connections with Other Disciplines
Students will connect dance to other disciplines.
research one choreographic work and one other artwork from the same culture and time period and examine how those works reflect the artistic/cultural/historical context of the time period.
research an interdisciplinary project using media technologies that present dance in a new or enhanced form.
Dance IV
Communication
Students will use dance as a way to create and communicate meaning.
create and perform (for a public audience) an individual dance conveying a personal experience, belief or theme.
Movement, Elements and Skills
Students will develop and practice movement elements in performing dance.
perform dance skills, demonstrating reliability, consistency, clarity and stylistic nuance.
refine technique/skills through self-evaluation and correction
Healthful Living
Students will relate dance to physical health.
devise a plan to assist in preparation for a career in dance.
research and analyze the challenges facing professional performer's in maintaining a healthy lifestyle.
Cultures and Historical Periods
Students will examine and demonstrate dance from various cultures and historical periods
perform techniques of various dance forms.
research and create a time line illustrating important dance events placing them in their cultural/historical/political contexts.
perform dances illustrating different historical/cultural/political contexts.
Critical and Creative Thinking Skills
Students will employ critical and creative thinking skills in dance
transfer how skills developed in dance to enhance present and future personal goals.
analyze the style of a choreographer or cultural form and create a dance in that style.
analyze issues of ethnicity, gender, social/economic class, age and/or physical condition in relation to dance and determine how these issues affect the art.
Choreography
Students will understand and apply choreographic principles, processes and structures.
create and perform, in small groups, a dance with coherence and aesthetic unity.
summarize their own creative process used in choreographing a dance phrase.
Connections with Other Disciplines
Students will connect dance to other disciplines.

compare and contrast one choreographic work to one other artwork from the same culture and time period in terms of how those works reflect the artistic/cultural/historical context of that same period.
create an interdisciplinary project using media technologies that present dance in a new or enhanced form.
